## Lessons Learned

- The named pipe reverse shell is more reliable than the standard bash redirect when the target has shell interpretation issues
- Never run `pkill nc` in AttackBox — it kills your own connection
- PHP web shells only need one line to work — simplicity is key
- Always use port 443 or 80 in real engagements — firewalls rarely block these
- File upload vulnerabilities are critical — always check what file types a web app accepts
- After getting a shell, first command should always be `ls /` to see what's on the system

## Defender's Perspective

- Validate and whitelist file upload types — never allow `.php`, `.asp`, `.jsp`
- Sanitise all user input before passing to system commands
- Use Web Application Firewalls (WAF) to detect command injection attempts
- Run web applications with minimal privileges — not as root
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP) headers
- Monitor for unusual outbound connections from web servers

